NVMe and NVMe over Fabrics

NVMe and NVMe over Fabrics (NVMe-oF) are critical for AI data storage and offer the low latency, high throughput, and scalability that is essential for handling large datasets and fast data processing. NVMe ensures rapid access to SSDs, whereas NVMe-oF extends these benefits across network fabrics to enable efficient remote access and management in distributed environments. Let’s take a closer look at each of these solutions.

NVMe

NVMe is a storage protocol that is optimized for modern SSDs and non-volatile memory technologies. Unlike older protocols such as Serial Advanced Technology Attachment (SATA) and serial-attached SCSI (SAS), which were designed for traditional hard drives, NVMe takes full advantage of the low latency, high speed, and parallelism that the NAND flash offers. Positioned directly on the Peripheral Component Interconnect Express (PCIe) bus, NVMe eliminates the bottlenecks of legacy protocols and enables faster data transfer rates, reduced latency, and more efficient data handling.

NVMe is increasingly critical in AI and ML workloads due to its high-speed data transfer capabilities, low latency, and ability to efficiently handle large volumes of data.

The key features and advantages of NVMe in AI are as follows:

  • High throughput and low latency: NVMe enables rapid data processing for AI workloads and minimizes storage bottlenecks during tasks like training neural networks.

  • Parallelism: Designed for modern CPUs, NVMe handles multiple I/O requests simultaneously, which is essential for processing large datasets in AI applications.

  • Scalability: NVMe scales efficiently with growing AI datasets, supports multiple drives without degrading performance, and is crucial for high-powered AI systems.

  • Real-time data processing: NVMe's fast read and write speeds support real-time AI inference and model training.

  • Data center optimization: NVMe reduces power, heat, and space requirements, and is therefore suitable for large-scale AI operations in modern data centers.

  • Edge computing: NVMe's speed and reliability are critical for real-time AI tasks at the edge, such as in autonomous vehicles and Internet of Things (IoT) devices.

NVMe over Fabrics

NVMe-oF is an extension of the NVMe protocol that is designed to enable high-performance access to NVMe storage devices across a network. NVMe was originally developed to connect directly to high-speed storage devices, like SSDs, using the PCIe bus. NVMe-oF allows benefits such as low latency and high throughput to be extended over various types of network fabrics, which enables remote storage access with minimal performance degradation.

The characteristics of NVMe-oF are as follows:

  • Purpose: NVMe-oF extends NVMe performance to networked storage and enables high-speed access in distributed environments.

  • Transport protocols

    1. NVMe over Fibre Channel (FC-NVMe): This protocol provides high reliability and performance over Fibre Channel networks.

    2. RDMA: This protocol provides low latency with direct memory access via RoCE, Internet Wide Area RDMA (iWARP), and InfiniBand.

    3. NVMe over TCP: This protocol provides flexible deployment over standard Ethernet with performance benefits.

  • Performance and latency: NVMe-oF maintains low latency and high throughput that is suitable for high-performance computing and AI.

  • Scalability and flexibility: NVMe-oF supports large, scalable storage pools for modern data centers.

  • Use cases: NVMe-oF is ideal for real-time analytics, databases, AI, and ML workloads.

NVMe-oF works with a controller and an option such as Fibre Channel or InfiniBand to transport data.

NVMe over Fabrics vs. NVMe

The following table compares NVMe and NVMe-oF and highlights their differences in protocol design, performance characteristics, scalability, transport protocols, use cases, latency, throughput, and flexibility.

Aspect

NVMe

NVMe-oF

Protocol

Designed for local storage access (SSDs)

Extends NVMe protocol over network fabrics

Performance

Very low latency, high throughput

Maintains low latency; throughput depends on the network

Scalability

Supports parallel command queues

Scalable within server or system; less scalable over the network

Transport protocols

PCI

Fibre Channel, RDMA (RoCE, iWARP, IB), TCP/IP

Use case

Local storage within a server

Remote access to NVMe storage over networks

Latency

Extremely low

Low, compared to traditional protocols, higher than NVMe

Throughput

High

High, but dependent on network infrastructure

Flexibility

Limited to local environment

Enables shared storage across distributed environments
